{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-projects-post-template-js","path":"/projects/20210305 - Oscillator Art/basic/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<hr>\n<p>Trying to visualize how two oscillators and a spinner working in tandem would result in a compound function of sorts...</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://souruly.github.io/P5-Playground/Tandem_Oscillators/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Link to Interactive Sketch</a></p>\n<p>Please open the link and then read along.</p>\n<p>One oscillator moves vertically, and other oscillator moves horizontally.(These are the default setting in the sketch. The angles can be changed. Please do!!)</p>\n<p>The X- coordinate of the horizontal oscillator and the Y-coordinate of the vertical oscilltor gives the position of the point. (Let's call this point P1)</p>\n<p>Initially the sketch was just going to be that much. But then I thought of adding one more level of complexity to the equation. So there's also a spinner\nwith center at P1 and given size and speed. The final point drawn on screen(in thick black lines) is the end point of this spinner.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/e72de/simple.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 50.67567567567568%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Simple Parametes\"\n        title=\"Simple Parametes\"\n        src=\"/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/fcda8/simple.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/12f09/simple.png 148w,\n/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/e4a3f/simple.png 295w,\n/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/fcda8/simple.png 590w,\n/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/efc66/simple.png 885w,\n/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/c83ae/simple.png 1180w,\n/static/5166ad3bd083436114f7793712cc3491/e72de/simple.png 1198w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>PS : If you let this run for a while, you'd see that the drawing returns to its start point. This depends on what initial parameters you choose. The simplest parameters where the values have a small LCM would converge faster, in one-two loops. Please play around with the sliders to have more complex drawings...</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/e72de/complex.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 50%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Complex Parameters\"\n        title=\"Complex Parameters\"\n        src=\"/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/fcda8/complex.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/12f09/complex.png 148w,\n/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/e4a3f/complex.png 295w,\n/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/fcda8/complex.png 590w,\n/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/efc66/complex.png 885w,\n/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/c83ae/complex.png 1180w,\n/static/ed7e1170756b6e87f258b8ab7480163e/e72de/complex.png 1198w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now ^this isn't even the most crazy you can get, I kept almost all the parametes as they were initialized. The only thing I changed was O1 speed, from 1 to 1.6. This, coupled with O2 speed of 2, forms makes a design with about 5-6 loops. There's a lot more room for complexity.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Art with Oscillators and Spinners","author":"Sourav Kulkarni","date":"29 April, 2020"},"excerpt":"Trying to visualize how two oscillators and a spinner working in tandem would result in a compound function of sorts... Link to Interactiveâ€¦","timeToRead":1}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/projects/20210305 - Oscillator Art/basic/","templatePath":"./src/templates/projects-post-template.js"}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}